---
import CalculatorLayout from "../../layouts/CalculatorLayout.astro";
import GratuityCalculator from "../../components/calculators/GratuityCalculator";
import { buildBreadcrumbs, buildFAQSchema, buildWebApplicationSchema } from "../../lib/seo";
import FAQAccordion from "../../components/ui/FAQAccordion.astro";
import RelatedLinks from "../../components/ui/RelatedLinks.astro";
import SourcesBlock from "../../components/ui/SourcesBlock.astro";
import AuthorByline from "../../components/ui/AuthorByline.astro";
import TrustBadge from "../../components/ui/TrustBadge.astro";

const faqs = [
  { question: "How is Saudi Arabia gratuity calculated?", answer: "Saudi EOSB: half month basic salary per year for the first 5 years, then one full month per year after 5 years. Calculated on last drawn basic salary plus housing allowance." },
  { question: "Do I get gratuity if I resign from a Saudi employer?", answer: "Resignation entitlements: less than 2 years = nothing; 2-5 years = one-third of gratuity; 5-10 years = two-thirds; over 10 years = full amount." },
  { question: "What salary component is used for Saudi gratuity?", answer: "Saudi gratuity is calculated on the last basic salary plus housing allowance, unlike UAE which uses basic salary only." },
  { question: "Is there a maximum cap on Saudi gratuity?", answer: "Saudi labor law does not specify an explicit maximum cap like the UAE's 2-year limit. The calculation is based entirely on the formula." },
  { question: "When must the employer pay gratuity in Saudi Arabia?", answer: "Saudi labor law requires payment of end-of-service benefits upon termination of employment. There is no specific statutory timeframe, but payment should be made promptly." },
  { question: "Can I lose gratuity for misconduct in Saudi Arabia?", answer: "Yes. Under Article 80 of Saudi labor law, employees dismissed for cause (gross misconduct) may forfeit gratuity rights." },
];
const breadcrumbs = [
  { name: "Home", url: "https://gulfexpathub.com/" },
  { name: "Saudi Arabia", url: "https://gulfexpathub.com/saudi-arabia/guide/" },
  { name: "Gratuity Calculator", url: "https://gulfexpathub.com/saudi-arabia/gratuity-calculator/" },
];
const schemas = [buildBreadcrumbs(breadcrumbs), buildFAQSchema(faqs), buildWebApplicationSchema("Saudi Arabia Gratuity Calculator 2026", "Calculate your Saudi EOSB using official MHRSD formulas.", "https://gulfexpathub.com/saudi-arabia/gratuity-calculator/")];
---

<CalculatorLayout title="Saudi Gratuity Calculator 2026: Free EOSB Computation" description="Calculate your Saudi end-of-service benefits for 2026. Official MHRSD formula with half-month and full-month tiers plus resignation penalties. Free tool." canonical="/saudi-arabia/gratuity-calculator/" schemas={schemas} breadcrumbs={[{ name: "Home", url: "/" }, { name: "Saudi Arabia", url: "/saudi-arabia/guide/" }, { name: "Gratuity Calculator", url: "/saudi-arabia/gratuity-calculator/" }]}>
  <AuthorByline />
  <h1 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-2">Saudi Arabia Gratuity Calculator 2026</h1>
  <p class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 mb-6">Calculate your Saudi end-of-service benefits using the official labor law formula. Instant browser-based calculations.</p>
  <TrustBadge />
  <div class="mt-6"><GratuityCalculator client:idle country="saudi" currency="SAR" countryName="Saudi Arabia" /></div>
  <div class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none mt-12">
    <h2>How Saudi Arabia EOSB is Calculated</h2>
    <p>The Saudi end-of-service benefit is governed by the Saudi Labour Law (Royal Decree No. M/51). The calculation uses the employee's last drawn basic salary plus housing allowance as the base figure. The formula is straightforward but differs from the UAE approach:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>First 5 years:</strong> Half month salary for each year of service (15 days per year).</li>
      <li><strong>After 5 years:</strong> One full month salary for each additional year of service (30 days per year).</li>
    </ul>
    <p>For example, an employee with SAR 12,000 basic salary (including housing) and 8 years of service: (12,000/2 x 5) + (12,000 x 3) = 30,000 + 36,000 = SAR 66,000 gross gratuity.</p>
    <p>Resignation penalties apply progressively: employees leaving before 2 years receive nothing, between 2-5 years receive one-third, between 5-10 years receive two-thirds, and after 10 years receive the full amount. These penalties do not apply when the employer initiates the termination (unless for cause).</p>
    <h2>Key Differences from UAE Gratuity</h2>
    <p>Saudi gratuity includes housing allowance in the calculation base, while UAE uses basic salary only. Saudi has no explicit cap on total gratuity, whereas UAE limits gratuity to 2 years of total salary. Saudi resignation penalties extend to 10 years for full entitlement, compared to 5 years in the UAE. Understanding these differences is crucial for professionals considering moves between Gulf countries.</p>

    <h2>Practical Examples</h2>
    <p><strong>Example 1 (3 years, employer termination):</strong> An employee earning SAR 10,000 basic + SAR 3,000 housing (SAR 13,000 total) with 3 years of service. Gratuity = (13,000/2) x 3 = SAR 19,500. Full amount since the employer terminated.</p>
    <p><strong>Example 2 (7 years, resignation):</strong> An employee earning SAR 15,000 basic + SAR 5,000 housing (SAR 20,000 total) with 7 years of service. Calculation: (20,000/2 x 5) + (20,000 x 2) = 50,000 + 40,000 = SAR 90,000 gross. Resignation penalty for 5-10 years = two-thirds. Actual payout: SAR 60,000.</p>
    <p><strong>Example 3 (12 years, resignation):</strong> An employee earning SAR 25,000 basic + SAR 8,000 housing (SAR 33,000 total) with 12 years of service. Calculation: (33,000/2 x 5) + (33,000 x 7) = 82,500 + 231,000 = SAR 313,500. No penalty for 10+ years of service, so the full amount is paid.</p>

    <h2>When to Expect Payment</h2>
    <p>Saudi labor law requires employers to settle all end-of-service entitlements upon termination but does not specify a fixed deadline like the UAE (14 days) or Qatar (7 days). In practice, most established employers process gratuity payments within the final salary cycle or within 30 days. If an employer delays payment, workers can file complaints through MHRSD's labor dispute resolution system. The General Organization for Social Insurance (GOSI) maintains employment records that can be used to verify service duration and salary history during disputes.</p>
  </div>
  <FAQAccordion faqs={faqs} />
  <SourcesBlock sources={[{ name: "Saudi MHRSD", url: "https://hrsd.gov.sa/" }, { name: "Saudi Labour Law - Royal Decree No. M/51", url: "https://hrsd.gov.sa/" }]} />
  <RelatedLinks links={[{ label: "Saudi Salary Calculator 2026", href: "/saudi-arabia/salary-calculator/" }, { label: "Saudi Salaries by Profession", href: "/saudi-arabia/salaries/" }, { label: "Saudi Labor Law Guide", href: "/saudi-arabia/labor-law/" }, { label: "UAE Gratuity Calculator", href: "/uae/gratuity-calculator/" }, { label: "Qatar Gratuity Calculator", href: "/qatar/gratuity-calculator/" }]} />
</CalculatorLayout>
